{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17487402","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17487402"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:09:31+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:09:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"342"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"342","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/342"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.59,0.2,0.04,0.06,0.11]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"342"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"56750"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"342","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/342"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"342"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42215"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"344"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2829"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2847"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17556"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"56750","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/56750"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old man is admitted to the medical ward with a one-day history of widespread abdominal pain. His medical history includes type 2 diabetes and chronic obstructive pulmonary disease. His medications include metformin 1g twice daily, 1mg semaglutide by subcutaneous injection weekly and Breo Ellipta inhaler once daily (fluticasone furoate and vilanterol trifenatate).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears pale and diaphoretic. His blood pressure is 110/70 mmHg, pulse 100/min, and temperature 38.4\u00b0C. His BMI is 34 kg/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E. Abdominal examination reveals generalised peritonitis. He undergoes an emergency sigmoid colectomy and end-colostomy for perforated diverticular disease. His recovery is complicated by a paralytic ileus, and six days after the operation, he develops a copious serosanguineous discharge at the lower part of the wound. The discharge soaks through the dressing. The wound is erythematous but is not warm or painful.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Deep wound dehiscence","Liquified wound haematoma","Streptococcal wound infection","Small bowel fistula","Staphylococcal wound infection"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe presence of a serosanguineous discharge from a wound at this stage after abdominal surgery is virtually diagnostic of a \u003Cstrong\u003Edeep wound dehiscence\u003C/strong\u003E. The increase in intra-abdominal pressure associated with the paralytic ileus would have been an important contributory factor, as would undertaking a procedure in contaminated surroundings. He also has several other factors that might contribute to poor wound healing, namely diabetes and chronic respiratory disease. The fever may be due to an inflammatory response or secondary infection associated with the dehiscence.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eliquified wound haematoma\u003C/strong\u003E would not produce any discharge. Instead, it would typically present as a fluctuant mass under the skin without external seepage, as the blood is contained within the haematoma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStreptococcal\u003C/strong\u003E or \u003Cstrong\u003Estaphylococcal wound infections\u003C/strong\u003E are more likely to produce pus and an inflammatory skin response (pain, warmth, erythema) rather than a serosanguineous discharge. These infections typically present with purulent discharge and significant localised inflammation, which is not described in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Esmall bowel fistula\u003C/strong\u003E is unlikely given the location of the surgical procedure in the large bowel, and would result in discharge of fluid from the intestinal tract. Additionally, the discharge from a fistula would typically be enteric in nature, not serosanguineous.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Deep wound dehiscence is a complication of surgical procedures that results in a pink serous seepage of blood-stained fluid at the surgical wound site.","Fever in the context of wound dehiscence may be due to an inflammatory response or secondary infection."],"references":["Rosen RD, Manna B. Wound Dehiscence. In: StatPearls [Internet]. 2021. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK551712/","Shanmugam VK, Fernandez SJ, Evans KK, McNish S, Banerjee AN, Couch KS, Mete M, Shara N. Postoperative wound dehiscence: Predictors and associations. Wound Repair Regen. 2015 Mar-Apr;23(2):184-90. doi: 10.1111/wrr.12268. PMID: 25683272; PMCID: PMC4587566."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42215"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"342"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42215","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/42215"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-21T15:43:32+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-21T16:43:28+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"342"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"56750"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"creat